Neither the Liber de Adventu Saoeonum, nor the Historia Romam, give us any intimation of the state of affairs in Northumberland on the death of Guthred3 but Symeon, in his History of the Charclz of Barbam, informs us that Alfred took the government into his own handsst Even then indeed the Danes had leaders of their own, whom they dignified with the title of kings, but their authority seems to have been persona] rather than territorial. Each could command the services of an organized host of his countrymen wherever the prospect of

plunder tempted him 3 but they reigned over no particular ,

locality ,- and we hear of them now in Northumberland, and now in Essex, Mercia, or East Anglia. When, on the accession of Edward the Elder to the throne of England, his cousin Ethelwald fied into Northumberland, he was received by these petty reyulz‘, and acknowledged as “king and prince of the kings.'' Such is the statement of Henry of Huntingdon, an historian well informed on northern affairs, who further ex- plains that the “Danish kings reigned in a confused manner, sometimes two, sometimes three, at the same time.”

Ethelwald was slain A.D. 905, and the following year we find “king Edward from necessity concluded a peace with the army both of East Anglia and of Northumberland,” over which these reyulz' now held command, freed from the control of any superior. ’

In 911, “the army among the Northumbrians broke the peace,'’ and being defeated by the forces of king Edward, two of their kings, Eowils and Halfdene, were slain.
